article.headline: (24) DAYTON 78, PRAIRIE VIEW 65
article.story: DAYTON, Ohio (AP) -- Sean Finn made sure Dayton capitalized on its height advantage over Prairie View. Finn, a 7-foot center, scored a career-high 27 points to lead No. 24 Dayton to a 78-65 victory over Prairie View A&M on Saturday. Finn shot 12-for-13 from the field and finished with 10 rebounds for his third straight double-double. "We had an advantage inside, and the guys did a good job of feeding me the ball," Finn said. "I think I did a decent job of being aggressive offensively, and when I made my first couple I got on a roll. The one I missed I will probably make nine out of 10 times." Keith Waleskowski added 16 points for Dayton, which won its ninth straight, the team's best start since opening the 1965-66 season 11-0. "Sean is playing as good as anyone, maybe anyone in the country, right now," said Dayton coach Brian Gregory. "He single-handedly won us that game tonight. I think he's more aggressive now." Kevin Cooper scored 20 and Tyrone Nelson added 18 for Prairie View. Nelson had a steal, made a layup and added a free throw after getting fouled to rally Prairie View (0-6) within five at 69-64 with 2:22 left. Finn countered with a dunk to stretch the lead to seven, and Prairie View never challenged again. "We've been watching Finn for a long time," Prairie View coach Jerry Francis Jr. said. "Big-time players step up and make big-time plays. I think he saw our front line, saw our intensity and matched it." Dayton outrebounded Prairie View 41-16, and the Flyers also beat Prairie View in transition. "I liked our energy. I liked our passion," Francis said. "I liked how we were moving, so I didn't want to get into our type of zone." Prairie View's 6-foot-11, 307-pound center, Roderick Riley, had nine points before fouling out with 8:35 remaining. Dayton went on a 10-3 run with 2:50 left in the first half, stretching a 30-26 lead to 40-29 by the break.
